1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,880
Every dataset can be dirty in its own way.

2
00:00:02,880 --> 00:00:06,540
It's impossible to list all of the issues that you may encounter with

3
00:00:06,540 --> 00:00:10,485
datasets that are out there in the wild after we've gathered them.

4
00:00:10,485 --> 00:00:13,260
But we can attempt to categorize them into issues so

5
00:00:13,260 --> 00:00:16,050
that we can more easily understand and identify them.

6
00:00:16,050 --> 00:00:19,560
Here, I'm going to be showing you five different attributes or

7
00:00:19,560 --> 00:00:23,370
dimensions of data quality corresponding to dirty datasets.

8
00:00:23,370 --> 00:00:26,445
These are accuracy, completeness,

9
00:00:26,445 --> 00:00:29,550
validity, consistency, and uniqueness.

10
00:00:29,550 --> 00:00:33,470
How do you know when your data contains all the info you need?

11
00:00:33,470 --> 00:00:37,220
Completeness is a metric that helps you understand whether your data is

12
00:00:37,220 --> 00:00:41,555
sufficient for you to answer interesting questions or solve your problem.

13
00:00:41,555 --> 00:00:44,900
Lack of completeness is typically shown in missing data.

14
00:00:44,900 --> 00:00:48,290
For example, if you are assessing data gathered in a survey,

15
00:00:48,290 --> 00:00:50,495
you might encounter missing values.

16
00:00:50,495 --> 00:00:53,930
This could resolve from participants that didn't want to share their information,

17
00:00:53,930 --> 00:00:56,350
so they skipped certain fields in your survey.

18
00:00:56,350 --> 00:01:00,845
In your dataset, this missing data may be represented as NaN values,

19
00:01:00,845 --> 00:01:04,580
signifying the absence of information in specific fields.

20
00:01:04,580 --> 00:01:09,245
One common way to fix completeness issues is removing the missing data.

21
00:01:09,245 --> 00:01:12,110
Alternatively, you can replace the missing values

22
00:01:12,110 --> 00:01:15,335
with default values or non-zero replacements.

23
00:01:15,335 --> 00:01:19,265
For example, when dealing with missing values in participants' age fields,

24
00:01:19,265 --> 00:01:21,395
you could fill in the gaps with the average age of

25
00:01:21,395 --> 00:01:23,750
all the participants who provided their age,

26
00:01:23,750 --> 00:01:26,705
rather than having the missing data points as NANs.

27
00:01:26,705 --> 00:01:29,900
This method helps maintain the integrity of your dataset while

28
00:01:29,900 --> 00:01:34,055
minimizing the impact of missing data on urinalysis.

29
00:01:34,055 --> 00:01:37,235
How well does your data meet certain constraints?

30
00:01:37,235 --> 00:01:40,400
Validity is a metric helping you understand how well

31
00:01:40,400 --> 00:01:43,310
your data conforms to a defined set of rules for data,

32
00:01:43,310 --> 00:01:45,185
which is also known as a schema.

33
00:01:45,185 --> 00:01:48,290
These rules can be based on real-world constraints.

34
00:01:48,290 --> 00:01:52,835
For example, if you are a health care practitioner gathering logs from a medical device,

35
00:01:52,835 --> 00:01:56,015
are there certain invalid values that are not within the right range,

36
00:01:56,015 --> 00:01:58,260
like 300 heartbeats per minute?

37
00:01:58,260 --> 00:02:01,315
They can also be rules specific to your data.

38
00:02:01,315 --> 00:02:03,865
For example, zip codes should be five integers,

39
00:02:03,865 --> 00:02:08,950
like 12345, but not in a float format, 12345.0.

40
00:02:08,950 --> 00:02:12,310
If data is not valid, it's not usable.

41
00:02:12,310 --> 00:02:15,460
In some cases, if a data point doesn't meet the rules of your data,

42
00:02:15,460 --> 00:02:18,850
you may even miss that it's there in the first place during assessment,

43
00:02:18,850 --> 00:02:22,315
only to discover it during the later stage, like cleaning.

44
00:02:22,315 --> 00:02:25,990
You can fix the validity issues by checking whether your data lies within

45
00:02:25,990 --> 00:02:30,295
the right range and checking the data types of your variables.

46
00:02:30,295 --> 00:02:34,085
How good is your data accurately representing the real world?

47
00:02:34,085 --> 00:02:37,645
Accuracy is a metric that helps you understand whether your data

48
00:02:37,645 --> 00:02:41,130
is accurately representing the reality that it aims to depict.

49
00:02:41,130 --> 00:02:45,800
The danger with inaccurate data is that it can still pass validity tests.

50
00:02:45,800 --> 00:02:47,315
But if you base your assumptions on it,

51
00:02:47,315 --> 00:02:49,655
your findings could be completely wrong.

52
00:02:49,655 --> 00:02:53,405
Consider the example where we're reporting data on patients' weights.

53
00:02:53,405 --> 00:02:54,845
Due to a faulty scale,

54
00:02:54,845 --> 00:02:56,960
all patients' weights in a given time period is

55
00:02:56,960 --> 00:03:00,365
recorded as five lbs heavier than their true weight.

56
00:03:00,365 --> 00:03:03,380
Although the values of the individual's weight will adhere to

57
00:03:03,380 --> 00:03:08,495
the defined schema and perform well on the validity metric, it's still inaccurate.

58
00:03:08,495 --> 00:03:11,420
It can be challenging to fix accuracy issues,

59
00:03:11,420 --> 00:03:13,130
but there are two ways to do this.

60
00:03:13,130 --> 00:03:15,230
One way is to keep checking the accuracy of

61
00:03:15,230 --> 00:03:17,890
your data source to ensure the data isn't faulty.

62
00:03:17,890 --> 00:03:21,470
The second approach is to cross-reference your data with other sources.

63
00:03:21,470 --> 00:03:24,620
For example, you may confirm an email address is accurate by

64
00:03:24,620 --> 00:03:28,405
associating it with the correct person on a subscription mail list.

65
00:03:28,405 --> 00:03:33,230
How good is your data at matching data across sources and following standard rules?

66
00:03:33,230 --> 00:03:37,310
Consistency is a metric that helps you understand two things.

67
00:03:37,310 --> 00:03:40,400
Whether your data is following a standard format and whether

68
00:03:40,400 --> 00:03:44,150
your data is info matches with information from other data sources.

69
00:03:44,150 --> 00:03:47,735
Inconsistency also poses a unique danger because

70
00:03:47,735 --> 00:03:51,245
inconsistent data can pass the validity and accuracy tests.

71
00:03:51,245 --> 00:03:54,035
Consider two examples of inconsistency.

72
00:03:54,035 --> 00:03:57,575
Let's talk about a tabular dataset where one column in your data

73
00:03:57,575 --> 00:04:01,425
represents birth dates of patients in the month, date, year format.

74
00:04:01,425 --> 00:04:07,225
Now another column represents sign-up dates of clients in the day, month, year format.

75
00:04:07,225 --> 00:04:10,780
These columns are both valid and accurate individually.

76
00:04:10,780 --> 00:04:13,750
But because of the lack of consistency in the format,

77
00:04:13,750 --> 00:04:16,210
you cannot reuse the same assessment and cleaning

78
00:04:16,210 --> 00:04:19,015
code to handle the date times for both columns,

79
00:04:19,015 --> 00:04:22,015
even though they represent the same type of data.

80
00:04:22,015 --> 00:04:25,585
Let's say now that the data within your dataset is consistent,

81
00:04:25,585 --> 00:04:29,365
it denotes all data recordings coming from the year 2023.

82
00:04:29,365 --> 00:04:32,650
However, another dataset stored elsewhere shows

83
00:04:32,650 --> 00:04:37,145
the data recordings coming from year 2022. Which one is correct?

84
00:04:37,145 --> 00:04:40,675
This data is both inconsistent and inaccurate.

85
00:04:40,675 --> 00:04:44,030
Consistency can sometimes be easy to address.

86
00:04:44,030 --> 00:04:46,400
In the first example, we would simply need to adopt

87
00:04:46,400 --> 00:04:49,580
the same standard format within the data across the columns.

88
00:04:49,580 --> 00:04:54,260
But fixing consistency issues can become challenging if the data is also inaccurate.

89
00:04:54,260 --> 00:04:56,780
In such cases, ensuring accuracy and

90
00:04:56,780 --> 00:05:01,880
cross-referencing data may be necessary before addressing consistency concerns.

91
00:05:01,880 --> 00:05:05,480
How good is your data in not containing duplicate values?

92
00:05:05,480 --> 00:05:08,540
Uniqueness is a metric that helps you understand whether

93
00:05:08,540 --> 00:05:11,735
there is duplicate or overlapping values in your data.

94
00:05:11,735 --> 00:05:16,070
Let's say you're collecting survey participant data on your marketing campaign.

95
00:05:16,070 --> 00:05:18,170
In particular, your data has two rows.

96
00:05:18,170 --> 00:05:21,875
One corresponds to the participant John K. Smith and other to John Smith,

97
00:05:21,875 --> 00:05:24,410
but these are actually the same person.

98
00:05:24,410 --> 00:05:27,710
Now you have two rows of data relating back to the same person.

99
00:05:27,710 --> 00:05:31,090
Which row has the right information and which can be deleted?

100
00:05:31,090 --> 00:05:34,220
Duplicated data can also unnecessarily

101
00:05:34,220 --> 00:05:37,535
increase the size of your data, consuming valuable resources.

102
00:05:37,535 --> 00:05:40,610
Additionally, it can cause downstream accuracy problems.

103
00:05:40,610 --> 00:05:43,490
Detecting and removing duplicate data is crucial to

104
00:05:43,490 --> 00:05:46,775
maintaining data quality and ensuring accurate insights.

105
00:05:46,775 --> 00:05:50,145
Now there are some ways to prevent data duplication and overlaps,

106
00:05:50,145 --> 00:05:53,480
including creating unique identifiers for each row,

107
00:05:53,480 --> 00:05:56,000
line, or the equivalent in your data.

108
00:05:56,000 --> 00:05:58,430
Other times, to fix uniqueness issues,

109
00:05:58,430 --> 00:06:01,010
you can programmatically catch duplicate values and

110
00:06:01,010 --> 00:06:05,100
remove the ones that are inaccurate or not needed regularly.

